  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I get my songs converted to karaoke or instrumental?",
  "response": "To convert your songs to karaoke or instrumental versions, you can use several methods or tools:\n\n1. **Online Services:**\n   - Websites such as PhonicMind, Vocal Remover, and Karaoke Version offer online tools to separate vocals from the instrumental track. These services usually process your uploaded audio file and provide you with vocal and instrumental versions separately.\n\n2. **Software:**\n   - **Audacity:** This free, open-source audio editing software can be used to reduce or isolate vocals. While not perfect, Audacity offers a vocal removal tool that works decently for many tracks.\n   - **Adobe Audition:** A more professional option, Adobe Audition has advanced features for isolating and removing vocals.\n   - **iZotope RX:** Known for its high-quality audio processing abilities, it can separate vocals from music but comes with a steeper learning curve and cost.\n\n3. **Mobile Apps:**\n   - **Moises:** This app uses AI to separate vocals and instruments, allowing you to create karaoke tracks on your smartphone.\n   - **Karaoke Maker:** Available on both Android and iOS, this app helps in creating karaoke versions by removing vocal tracks.\n\n4. **Using MIDI Files:**\n   - If MIDI files of your songs are available, you can use them to generate a karaoke version. MIDI files contain musical note data but no vocals, making them perfect for this purpose. Software like Synthesia or GarageBand can be used to play and modify MIDI files.\n\n5. **DIY Approach:**\n   - You can try phase cancellation techniques, which involve inverting one stereo channel and mixing it with the other to reduce the vocals. This method requires some audio editing knowledge and doesn\u2019t always provide clean results.\n\n6. **Hiring Professionals:**\n   - Consider hiring a professional audio engineer or using a freelance service like Fiverr to get custom instrumental or karaoke tracks made.\n\nRemember, the effectiveness of each method may vary depending on the complexity of the song and how the vocals are mixed. Some songs will convert better than others due to their production techniques.",
